{{refimprove|date=May 2016}} {{Jurassic}} In the [[geologic timescale]], the '''Kimmeridgian''' is an [[age (geology)|age]] or [[stage (stratigraphy)|stage]] in the [[Late Jurassic|Late or Upper Jurassic]] [[epoch (geology)|epoch]] or [[series (stratigraphy)|series]]. It spans the time between 157.3 ± 1.0 [[annum|Ma]] and 152.1 ± 0.9 Ma (million years ago). The Kimmeridgian follows the [[Oxfordian (stage)|Oxfordian]] and precedes the [[Tithonian]].<ref>For a detailed version of the [[International Commission on Stratigraphy|ICS]]' timescale, see Gradstein ''et al.'' (2004)</ref>
==Stratigraphic definition== The Kimmeridgian stage takes its name from the village of [[Kimmeridge]] on the [[Dorset]] coast, [[England]]. The name was introduced in literature by Swiss geologist [[Jules Thurmann]] in 1832.{{citation needed||date=May 2016}} The [[Kimmeridge Clay Formation]] has its name from the same [[type locality (geology)|type location]]. It is the source for about 95% of the [[petroleum]] in the [[North Sea]].{{citation needed||date=May 2016}}
Historically, the term Kimmeridgian has been used in two different ways. The base of the interval is the same but the top was defined by British [[stratigrapher]]s as the base of the [[Portlandian]] (''sensu anglico'') whereas in France the top was defined as the base of the Tithonian (''sensu gallico''). The differences have not yet been fully resolved; {{as of|2004}} Tithonian is the uppermost stage of the Jurassic in the timescale of the [[International Commission on Stratigraphy|ICS]].<ref>[http://www.es.ucl.ac.uk/people/bown/ISJS31.pdf INTERNATIONAL SUBCOMMISSION ON JURASSIC STRATIGRAPHY, Newsletter 31, Edited by Nicol Morton and Paul Bown, August 2004]</ref>
The base of the Kimmeridgian is at the first appearance of [[ammonite]] species ''[[Pictonia|Pictonia baylei]]'' in the [[stratigraphic column]].<ref name="GSSP">{{cite web|title=Global Boundary Stratotype Section and Point (GSSP) of the International Commission on Stratigraphy|url=http://www.stratigraphy.org/gssp/|website=GSSP Table - All Periods|publisher=International Commission on Stratigraphy|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref> A global reference profile for the base (the [[GSSP]] of the Kimmeridgian stage) had in 2009 not yet been assigned.{{citation needed||date=May 2016}} The top of the Kimmeridgian (the base of the Tithonian) is at the first appearance of ammonite species ''[[Hybonoticeras|Hybonoticeras hybonotum]]''. It also coincides with the top of [[magnetostratigraphy|magnetic anomaly]] M22An.<ref name="GSSP" />
===Subdivision=== The Kimmeridgian is sometimes{{weasel inline|date=May 2016}} subdivided into Upper and Lower substages.{{citation needed||date=May 2016}} In the [[Tethys Ocean|Tethys domain]], the Kimmeridgian contains seven ammonite [[biozone]]s:{{citation needed||date=May 2016}} *zone of ''[[Hybonoticeras|Hybonoticeras beckeri]]'' *zone of ''[[Aulacostephanus|Aulacostephanus eudoxus]]'' *zone of ''[[Aspidoceras|Aspidoceras acanthicum]]'' *zone of ''[[Crussoliceras|Crussoliceras divisum]]'' *zone of ''[[Ataxioceras|Ataxioceras hypselocyclum]]'' *zone of ''[[Sutneria|Sutneria platynota]]'' *zone of ''[[Idoceras|Idoceras planula]]''
